<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_dictionary` row that
    declares the `person` Reference field on the `x_[scope]_case_party`
    custom table inside the scoped application `x_[scope]_case_management`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim) for x_[scope]_case_party:

        Field    Type                    Constraints
        person   Reference -> sys_user   Conditional: required if party_type = Person

    Per AAP Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications):
        "Polymorphic association via single-table choice + UI Policy -
         case_party collapses ArkCase's two association tables
         (acm_person_assoc, acm_person_org_assoc) into one ServiceNow table
         with a Choice discriminator (party_type) and a UI Policy that
         conditionally shows person (reference -> sys_user) or organization
         (reference -> core_company)."

    THIS FIELD IS THE PERSON HALF OF THE POLYMORPHIC PARTY MODEL. Together
    with its sibling `organization` field
    (../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_party_organization.xml -> Reference ->
    core_company), `person` represents one of two mutually exclusive
    sub-shapes of a party row, with the choice between them driven by the
    `party_type` discriminator
    (../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_party_party_type.xml). When party_type =
    Person, this `person` reference is required and visible while
    `organization` is hidden and ignored. When party_type = Organization,
    this `person` reference is hidden and ignored while `organization` is
    required and visible. The conditional show/hide and conditional
    mandatoriness are NOT enforced at the dictionary level here - they
    are enforced by the UI Policy at
    ../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml. THIS
    dictionary entry simply DECLARES that the column exists, that it is a
    Reference to sys_user, and that the dictionary-level mandatory flag
    is FALSE so the polymorphism remains correct (Organization-typed
    rows must be allowed to save with `person` empty).

    Critical behaviors that depend on this field (AAP Sections 0.4.3,
    0.4.4, 0.5.7, 0.7.4):

      1. CONDITIONAL VISIBILITY VIA UI POLICY
         (../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml)
         Per AAP Section 0.1.2 verbatim: "The case_party polymorphic
         conditional fields (person shown when party_type = Person;
         organization shown when party_type = Organization) are
         implemented via UI Policies on the form." The UI Policy at the
         path above runs on the case_party form and:
           * When party_type = Person:   sets person.visible = true,
                                         person.mandatory = true,
                                         organization.visible = false,
                                         organization.mandatory = false
           * When party_type = Organization: sets person.visible = false,
                                             person.mandatory = false,
                                             organization.visible = true,
                                             organization.mandatory = true
         The UI Policy READS this dictionary entry's element name
         (`person`) to know which form field to manipulate. Without
         THIS dictionary entry, the UI Policy could not find a column
         named `person` to bind its actions against, and the conditional
         visibility would silently fail to apply. Note that the UI
         Policy operates at the FORM layer only - server-side
         GlideRecord.insert() / Table API POST do NOT run UI Policies,
         which is why mandatory=false at the dictionary level and the
         "Conditional: required if party_type=Person" semantics are
         enforced by THIS particular UI Policy combined with the
         platform's form rendering, NOT by a hard mandatory=true flag
         that would break Organization-typed rows.

      2. PERSON HALF OF THE POLYMORPHISM-COLLAPSE PATTERN
         (../tables/x_[scope]_case_party.xml,
          ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_party_party_type.xml,
          ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_party_organization.xml)
         AAP Section 0.4.3's "Polymorphic association via single-table
         choice + UI Policy" pattern collapses ArkCase's TWO source
         JPA entities (PersonAssociation -> acm_person_assoc and
         PersonOrganizationAssociation -> acm_person_org_assoc) into
         the SINGLE ServiceNow table x_[scope]_case_party, where:
           * party_type carries the discriminator (Person | Organization)
           * THIS `person` field carries the sys_user pointer when
             party_type = Person (replacing PersonAssociation.person
             @ManyToOne(Person) and PersonOrganizationAssociation.person
             @ManyToOne(Person))
           * organization carries the core_company pointer when
             party_type = Organization (replacing
             PersonOrganizationAssociation.organization
             @ManyToOne(Organization))
         The collapse is semantically lossless within the POC scope
         (AAP Section 0.3.1) because:
           * The POC's only "thing parties attach to" is the case
             (parent linkage handled by ../dictionary/
             x_[scope]_case_party_case.xml), not the multi-target
             attach-anywhere pattern of PersonAssociation.parentId/
             parentType in ArkCase.
           * The PersonOrganizationAssociation pattern (a Person tied
             to an Organization, with both references on the same row)
             is OUT OF SCOPE per AAP Section 0.3.2's "no PII or real
             customer data" / "synthetic only" constraint and the POC's
             enumerated case-party feature set, which only requires
             attaching a Person OR an Organization (mutually
             exclusive) to a case. A future enhancement could re-add
             the dual-reference shape, but it is not in scope.
         Note that AAP Section 0.5.7's "Conditional: required if
         party_type = Person" qualifier is the canonical contract for
         this field's mandatoriness - it is REQUIRED, but only in the
         context of Person-typed rows. The dictionary's hard
         mandatory=false ensures that Organization-typed rows can save
         with this field empty; the UI Policy reinstates a
         conditional mandatory=true at the form layer when the chosen
         party_type is Person.

      3. AGENT/MANAGER FORM EDITING WITH OOB sys_user PICKER
         (parent table ../tables/x_[scope]_case_party.xml automatic
          form layout per AAP Section 0.4.4 "Internal user UI"
          requirements)
         AAP Section 0.4.4 declares: "the internal user UI is provided
         by ServiceNow's automatic native list and form views for the
         three custom tables." When a case_manager or case_agent opens
         a case_party form with party_type = Person, the auto-rendered
         picker for THIS field surfaces ALL active sys_user records
         via the platform's standard reference-field combobox/typeahead.
         The user can search the sys_user directory by user_name,
         first_name, last_name, or email to find the correct person
         to associate with the case. Once selected, the platform
         persists the chosen user's 32-character sys_id in this column.
         The picker auto-derefences the user's display column
         (user_name or name, depending on sys_user dictionary
         configuration) for human-readable rendering on the form, in
         the case_party list view, and in the case form's Related List
         of parties. This deferred dereference is what allows the seed
         data and the demo cases to reference users by stable
         human-readable user_name (e.g., x_[scope]_demo_agent) rather
         than by hard-coded sys_id, per AAP Section 0.7.2's
         "no-hardcoded-sys_id constraint."

      4. ACL "ASSIGNED ONLY" CASCADE FOR CASE_AGENT
         (../acl/x_[scope]_case_party_*.xml)
         Per AAP Section 0.5.6: case_agent has "Assigned only" CRUD
         access. For parties, "Assigned only" propagates THROUGH the
         parent `case` reference (declared in
         ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_party_case.xml), NOT through THIS
         `person` field. A case_agent does NOT gain or lose access to
         a party row based on whether this `person` field happens to
         point at the case_agent themselves - access is determined
         solely by the parent case's assigned_agent / assigned_group
         columns. This means a case_agent who is associated to a case
         AS A PARTY (e.g., as a Witness) does NOT thereby gain edit
         access to OTHER parties on the same case unless they are
         also the case's assigned_agent or in the case's assigned_group.
         This separation is intentional: the AAP's authorization model
         explicitly distinguishes "owner" (assigned_agent) from
         "associated" (party.person), and only the former confers
         operational access. The party.person column thus carries
         RECORD-OF-ASSOCIATION semantics, not RECORD-OF-OWNERSHIP
         semantics - a critical distinction inherited from the source
         model where ArkCase's PersonAssociation tracked associations
         independently of the assignee.

      5. PORTAL-LOOKUP FIELD WHITELIST EXCLUSION
         (../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup.xml)
         Per AAP Section 0.7.4: "the lookup page returns ONLY status,
         subject, opened_date - no internal fields exposed." Party
         data (including the `person` and `organization` references)
         is NOT exposed by the portal status-lookup endpoint. An
         anonymous external requester querying their case status by
         number sees only the three whitelisted top-level case fields
         and learns nothing about who else is associated to the case
         (whether by name, role, or organizational affiliation). This
         is a strict-by-default privacy posture aligned with AAP
         Section 0.3.2's no-PII-exposure stance. THIS dictionary entry
         therefore deliberately does NOT participate in any
         portal-facing schema; the field is INTERNAL-ONLY by
         construction.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-person-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/person/model/PersonAssociation.java
        lines 86-88:
            @ManyToOne(cascade = { CascadeType.REFRESH, CascadeType.DETACH,
                CascadeType.PERSIST, CascadeType.MERGE }, optional = false)
            @JoinColumn(name = "cm_person_assoc_person_id", nullable = false)
            private Person person;
        ArkCase's PersonAssociation entity carried a NOT-NULL @ManyToOne
        relationship to the Person domain entity (a separate
        @Entity-mapped JPA class living in the acm-person-plugin
        alongside Organization, with its own dedicated table acm_person
        and a rich sub-schema covering names, contact info, identifiers,
        and aliases). The @JoinColumn was named cm_person_assoc_person_id
        and was DECLARED NOT NULL (`nullable = false`), with a default
        cascade set covering REFRESH, DETACH, PERSIST, and MERGE - that
        is, the entire JPA lifecycle except orphan removal. The entity
        also lazy-instantiated a Person if the field was null at getter
        time (PersonAssociation.java lines 145-152's `getPerson()`
        method's `if (person == null) { person = new Person(); }` pattern),
        which was a defensive measure against Hibernate proxy
        materialization bugs but did not affect the table-level NOT NULL
        constraint.

        The ServiceNow target ALTERS this contract in two ways (AAP
        Sections 0.1.2, 0.4.3, 0.5.7):
          * The Person domain entity is REPLACED by the OOB sys_user
            table. ArkCase's separate Person/Organization directory
            (mapped to acm_person/acm_organization) is OUT OF SCOPE
            per AAP Section 0.3.2's enumerated POC feature set - the
            POC has no requirement for a directory of "people the
            organization knows about" beyond ServiceNow's standard
            sys_user roster, which already covers internal users
            (case_manager / case_agent / case_viewer demo accounts) and
            could be extended with synthetic sys_user records to
            represent external requesters if needed. Replacing Person
            with sys_user gains: referential integrity (the sys_user
            picker enforces existing-row selection); single source of
            truth (the same table backing authentication, role
            assignment, dashboard scoping); and zero dependency on a
            separate person-directory plugin. The trade-off is the
            loss of ArkCase's richer Person sub-schema (multiple
            phones, addresses, identifications, aliases) which is
            irrelevant to the POC's case-association feature set.
          * The NOT NULL constraint is REPLACED by a CONDITIONAL mandatory
            constraint enforced by UI Policy. ArkCase's
            cm_person_assoc_person_id was unconditionally NOT NULL
            because PersonAssociation rows ALWAYS represented a
            person-to-parent association (the parent could be a case,
            but the Person side of the association was always present
            by definition). In the ServiceNow target, x_[scope]_case_party
            collapses two source tables into one polymorphic table; for
            Organization-typed rows, this `person` column MUST be empty
            (the polymorphism semantics demand it), which is incompatible
            with a hard NOT NULL constraint. The CONDITIONAL mandatoriness
            (required only when party_type = Person) is the
            ServiceNow-idiomatic equivalent.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-person-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/person/model/PersonOrganizationAssociation.java
        lines 82-84:
            @ManyToOne(cascade = { CascadeType.REFRESH, CascadeType.DETACH,
                CascadeType.PERSIST }, optional = false)
            @JoinColumn(name = "cm_person_id", nullable = false)
            private Person person;
        The SECOND ArkCase entity that contributes person-pointing data
        to the polymorphism collapse. PersonOrganizationAssociation
        also carried a NOT NULL @ManyToOne to Person (with @JoinColumn
        cm_person_id, distinct from the cm_person_assoc_person_id used
        by PersonAssociation), but the cascade set was slightly narrower
        (no MERGE), reflecting different entity-lifecycle semantics
        between the two source tables. In ArkCase, both source tables
        ALWAYS had a non-null Person pointer; the polymorphic collapse
        in the ServiceNow target permits empty `person` only on
        Organization-typed rows, which represent the
        PersonOrganizationAssociation pattern in shape (an
        organization participating in the case-party model) WITHOUT the
        bundled Person reference (which is OUT OF SCOPE per AAP
        Section 0.3.2). If a future enhancement wanted to reproduce
        the dual-reference (Person + Organization on the same row)
        shape of PersonOrganizationAssociation, a third party_type
        choice (e.g., "PersonViaOrganization") plus relaxed
        mandatoriness on both reference fields would suffice; that is
        not in scope here.

      - The field name is `person` (lowercase, 6 chars, no prefix; NOT
        `person_ref`, NOT `person_id`, NOT `person_user`, NOT
        `assigned_person`) per AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim. This single
        unqualified word was deliberately chosen by the AAP for two
        reasons:
          * It mirrors the parallel ArkCase JPA field name `person`
            (PersonAssociation.java line 88, PersonOrganizationAssociation.java
            line 84), preserving naming familiarity for any future
            developer migrating from the source codebase.
          * It complements the sibling `organization` field name on
            the same table (also a single unqualified word; the same
            naming pattern is used by AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim for
            BOTH polymorphism halves), making the polymorphism-collapse
            pattern visually obvious in the field list.
        The dictionary-level column_label "Person" (capitalized,
        title-case) is consistent with the AAP-implied human-readable
        label set across the data model (e.g., "Subject", "Type",
        "Status", "Priority" - all single capitalized words).

      - ArkCase's Person entity used a MySQL InnoDB BIGINT primary key
        with no explicit length cap; the @JoinColumn cm_person_id /
        cm_person_assoc_person_id stored that bigint. The ServiceNow
        target uses the standard 32-character Reference-field width to
        store the sys_id of the chosen sys_user row; the platform's
        auto-generated form picker, list view, and report builder all
        dereference to the user's display column for human-readable
        display via the OOB sys_user dictionary's display=true
        configuration.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: `<name>` resolves to
        `x_[scope]_case_party` within the scoped application, and
        `<sys_scope>` / `<sys_package>` bind THIS dictionary record to
        the same scope by `source` attribute lookup. The `<reference>`
        element resolves to OOB `sys_user` by table name (NOT by
        sys_id), preserving zero-hardcoded-sys_id compliance. NO
        global-scope writes - the OOB `sys_user` table is REFERENCED
        but never modified.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>`,
        `<sys_package>`, and `<reference>` text-node values resolve by
        scope source name and table name respectively, not by literal
        sys_id. The `<sys_id>` text-node value is THIS record's own
        deterministic primary key (MD5 of the canonical field
        identifier `x_[scope]_case_party.person` =
        d9b322d03c2bb79ef07a261e2f686cb4) and is NOT a reference to any
        other record. Per AAP Section 0.7.2 this scheme guarantees that
        a fresh PDI re-import of the Update Set produces byte-identical
        sys_id values, which is necessary for round-trip-verify
        (../scripts/round_trip_verify.md) zero-error preview.
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved per AAP
        convention; the PDI auto-assigns the actual scope id at App
        Engine Studio creation time and substitutes it into every
        occurrence at export.
      - mandatory=false at the dictionary level (CRITICAL: AAP Section
        0.5.7's "Conditional: required if party_type = Person" is a
        POLYMORPHISM-LEVEL constraint enforced by the UI Policy at
        ../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml, NOT
        a FIELD-LEVEL constraint enforced by the dictionary). Setting
        this to true would prevent Organization-typed party rows from
        being saved (since they have no person), which DIRECTLY
        contradicts the polymorphism collapse pattern (AAP Section
        0.4.3) and the AAP Section 0.5.7 enumerated party_type list
        (Person, Organization, both supported on the same table). The
        UI Policy reinstates conditional mandatoriness at the form
        layer when party_type = Person, which is the correct
        ServiceNow-idiomatic enforcement point for choice-driven
        field requiredness.
      - read_only=false: case_manager and case_agent both edit this
        field directly when associating a person party to a case. The
        auto-generated New Party form on the case's Related List
        pre-populates the parent `case` reference, then surfaces the
        party_type picker; once Person is selected, the UI Policy
        reveals THIS person field for editing.
      - default_value (empty): no automatic person assignment. The
        AAP Section 0.5.7 specification is "Conditional: required if
        party_type = Person" - which inherently means there is no
        sensible platform-wide default. The user explicitly chooses
        the person at form-fill time.
      - audit=false: per AAP Section 0.3.1 minimal-change clause and
        consistent with the sibling Reference / DateTime / Choice /
        String fields in this same dictionary set. The sys_history_set
        / sys_audit infrastructure on demand still captures party-row
        audit events at the row level via the platform's standard
        sys_* audit columns; per-field audit on `person` would inflate
        sys_audit storage with low-value entries (a party row's
        person rarely changes after initial assignment).
      - max_length=32: the standard ServiceNow Reference-field width.
        The dictionary stores the 32-character lowercase-hex sys_id of
        the referenced sys_user row as the actual column value; the
        platform's auto-generated form picker, list view, and report
        builder all dereference to the user's display column for
        human-readable display via the OOB sys_user dictionary's
        display=true column.
      - choice=0: this is a Reference field, NOT a Choice field. The
        sibling sys_choice_* records under ../choices/ apply only to
        the `type`, `status`, `priority`, `pending_reason`,
        `case_task.type`, `case_task.status`, and `case_party.party_type`
        columns - none are needed here.
      - choice_field, choice_table empty: same reason as choice=0
        above.
      - reference=sys_user: OOB ServiceNow user table. AAP Section
        0.5.7 specifies this exact target table by name (NOT `task`,
        NOT `users`, NOT `sys_user_pwd`, NOT any other variant). The
        platform resolves the table-name cross-reference at Update
        Set import time by querying sys_db_object.name; sys_user is
        always present on every PDI as part of the OOB schema, so no
        explicit dependency-ordering is needed (in contrast to
        ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_party_case.xml whose
        `<reference>x_[scope]_case</reference>` requires
        ../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml to be loaded first).
      - reference_cascade_rule (empty): default platform behavior,
        which is "do nothing on referenced-record deletion." If a
        sys_user is deleted (a rare administrative operation
        typically gated by global ACLs), party rows retain the
        orphaned reference; this is acceptable for the POC since
        user deletion is a global-admin-level operation and is rare
        in practice. The sibling
        ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_assigned_agent.xml uses the same
        empty cascade rule for the same reason (both point at
        sys_user). AAP does not specify a cascade rule for this
        column.
      - reference_qual, reference_qual_condition (empty): no filter
        on which users may be selected. ANY active sys_user is
        eligible at the picker level. AAP Section 0.5.7 does not
        require filtering by role, group membership, or any other
        criterion - a party may be ANY user, including users with
        no scoped roles (e.g., an external complainant whose sys_user
        record was synthetically created at intake time with no role
        grants). A future enhancement could add a dynamic ref qual
        such as `active=true` or `active=true^locked_out=false`, but
        that is not in scope per AAP Section 0.3.1's MINIMAL CHANGE
        CLAUSE.
      - use_reference_qualifier=simple: standard ServiceNow setting
        when no advanced (scripted) reference qualifier is in use.
      - dynamic_ref_qual (empty): no dynamic reference qualifier - see
        reference_qual rationale above.
      - reference_floor, reference_key, reference_type (empty):
        standard defaults for a basic table-to-table reference; no
        advanced reference semantics (typeahead override, reference
        floor table, document reference, etc.) are needed here.
      - element_reference=false: this is a TABLE reference, not an
        ELEMENT reference (which would point at a specific dictionary
        column on another table). AAP specifies a row-level reference
        target.
      - table_reference=false: this is NOT a "Document ID" / "Table"
        polymorphic reference (which is what `glide_var` style fields
        on the OOB task table use to reference any-table-any-row). It
        is a fixed-target reference to sys_user only. Note that the
        polymorphism in case_party operates at a HIGHER level - via
        the party_type Choice plus the sibling person/organization
        Reference fields - not via a table-level polymorphic
        reference like Document ID would provide.
      - text_index=false: Reference fields are not full-text-indexed.
        Searches by user are performed via GlideRecord addJoinQuery
        against sys_user on its sys_id column; full-text indexing of
        the 32-char sys_id has no value.
      - unique=false: a single user may correctly be a party on
        multiple cases (e.g., a known witness who appears on many
        complaint cases). Uniqueness on this column would be
        semantically wrong and would prevent the seed data from
        creating multiple party rows pointing at the same demo user.
        AAP Section 0.7.4 minimum demo-data thresholds explicitly
        require "at least one Person and one Organization party per
        demo case" with no constraint that Person rows must reference
        DIFFERENT users across cases - in fact, the seed plan reuses
        synthetic users across multiple demo cases for compactness.
      - virtual=false: this is a stored column, not a calculated /
        virtual derivation. The actual sys_id of the chosen sys_user
        row is persisted on every party record.
      - spell_check=false: Reference fields hold a 32-char sys_id and
        the platform renders the dereferenced display value at view
        time; spell-check is meaningless for the persisted value and
        would be misapplied to the dereferenced human-name display.
      - No PII: the field stores a 32-char sys_id pointer to a user
        record; the user record itself stores categorical
        organizational identity (synthetic user_name, fabricated
        display name, fabricated email at the demo seed level only)
        per AAP Section 0.7.2 ("synthetic only"). The seed users at
        ../seed-data/users/sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_*.xml are
        fabricated synthetic accounts (one per role: case_manager,
        case_agent, case_viewer); no real names, real email
        addresses, or PII derived from the source ArkCase database
        are placed in this column at any point in the build.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      - This record MUST load AFTER:
          * ../tables/x_[scope]_case_party.xml (parent table; `<name>`
            here references the scoped party table by name; the
            platform requires the table to exist before its dictionary
            entries can be created)
          * sys_user (OOB; always present on every PDI; never modified
            by this Update Set per AAP Section 0.3.2)
      - This record MUST load BEFORE the consumers that read or write
        the `person` column on x_[scope]_case_party:
          * ../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml
            (the polymorphism UI Policy that toggles visibility/
            mandatoriness of THIS field based on party_type; the
            policy's actions reference the column by element name
            `person`, which requires this dictionary entry to exist
            so the platform's UI Policy editor can resolve the
            reference at design time AND at form-render time)
          * ../acl/x_[scope]_case_party_*.xml (table-level ACLs on
            the case_party table; while THIS field is not directly
            named in any ACL condition, the table-level ACLs read
            ALL fields on the row and therefore implicitly cover the
            `person` field's read/write authorization within the
            case_agent "Assigned only" condition that dot-walks
            current.case.assigned_agent and current.case.assigned_group)
          * ../seed-data/parties/x_[scope]_case_party_demo_*.xml
            (synthetic demo parties that populate THIS field for
            party_type = Person rows by lookup of the demo user's
            user_name attribute via the seed_demo_data.js script -
            never via hard-coded sys_id, per AAP Section 0.7.2 the
            no-hardcoded-sys_id constraint applies to flows, ACL
            conditions, scripts, seed data, UI Policies, UI Actions,
            Business Rules, and client scripts; AAP Section 0.7.4
            minimum demo-data thresholds explicitly require "at
            least one Person and one Organization party per demo
            case to exercise the polymorphic UI policy" - which
            mandates that the demo seed contains rows with party_type
            = Person and a populated person reference)
          * ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js (the idempotent seed script
            that creates the demo party rows; for each Person-typed
            demo party it performs:
                var personGr = new GlideRecord('sys_user');
                personGr.addQuery('user_name', '<demo-user-user-name>');
                personGr.query();
                if (personGr.next()) { partyGr.person = personGr.sys_id; }
            to resolve the user sys_id at seed time, never via
            hard-coded literals)
-->
<record_update table="sys_dictionary">
    <sys_dictionary action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <array>false</array>
        <attributes/>
        <audit>false</audit>
        <calculation/>
        <choice>0</choice>
        <choice_field/>
        <choice_table/>
        <column_label>Person</column_label>
        <comments>Reference to sys_user. Conditional: required when party_type=Person (enforced by UI Policy in ../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml). Replaces ArkCase PersonAssociation.person and PersonOrganizationAssociation.person @ManyToOne (which targeted ArkCase's Person entity; here we leverage OOB sys_user instead). Person half of the polymorphism collapse pattern (AAP Section 0.4.3): when party_type=Person this field is required and visible while the sibling organization field is hidden; when party_type=Organization this field is hidden while organization is required. Dictionary-level mandatory=false to allow Organization-typed rows to save with this field empty - the conditional mandatoriness is enforced by the UI Policy. Cascade rule is empty (default "no cascade" - deleting a sys_user does NOT auto-cascade-delete party rows; manual cleanup of orphaned references is acceptable). Seed data resolves the user sys_id by lookup of sys_user.user_name via ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js (no hardcoded sys_ids, per AAP Section 0.7.2).</comments>
        <create_roles/>
        <default_value/>
        <defaultsort/>
        <delete_roles/>
        <dependent/>
        <dependent_on_field/>
        <display>true</display>
